Title : The Mark on the Wall
Text : '''''The Mark on the Wall''''' is the first published story by [[Virginia Woolf]].<ref name="MaoWalkowitz2010">{{cite book|author1=Douglas Mao|author2=Rebecca L. Walkowitz|title=Bad Modernisms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vPs7GDKCvJUC&pg=PA124|date=1 July 2010|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0-8223-8782-4|pages=124–}}</ref> It was published in 1917 as part of the first collection of short stories written by Virginia Woolf and her husband, [[Leonard Woolf]], called ''Two Stories''.<ref name="Goldman2006">{{cite book|author=Jane Goldman|title=The Cambridge Introduction to Virginia Woolf|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=74oONFoebsAC&pg=PA88|date=14 September 2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-45788-0|pages=88–}}</ref> It was later published in New York in 1921 as part of another collection entitled ''[[Monday or Tuesday]]''.

==Summary==

''The Mark on the Wall'' is written in the first person, as a "[[Stream of consciousness (narrative mode)|stream of consciousness]]" monologue.<ref name="Freedman1980">{{cite book|author=Ralph Freedman|title=Virginia Woolf: Revaluation and Continuity, a Collection of Essays|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t4cQKKKIKM0C&pg=PA53|date=January 1980|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-03980-3|pages=53–}}</ref> The narrator notices a mark on the wall, and muses on the workings of the mind.<ref name="Sellers2010">{{cite book|author=Susan Sellers|title=The Cambridge Companion to Virginia Woolf|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZpQ4GG-Ng2gC&pg=PA42|date=18 February 2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-89694-8|pages=42–}}</ref>  Themes of religion, self-reflection,<ref name="Welsh2010">{{cite book|author=Dave Welsh|title=Underground Writing: The London Tube from George Gissing to Virginia Woolf|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0kUH3si46mkC&pg=PA180|year=2010|publisher=Liverpool University Press|isbn=978-1-84631-223-6|pages=180–}}</ref> nature, and uncertainty are explored. The narrator reminisces about the development of thought patterns, beginning in childhood.<ref name="Fraser2011">{{cite book|author=Jennifer Margaret Fraser|title=Be a Good Soldier: Children's Grief in English Modernist Novels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJW-NdyUytkC&pg=PA157|date=1 January 2011|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-1-4426-4313-0|pages=157–}}</ref>

==Reception==
Woolf's style in ''The Mark on the Wall'' has been frequently analyzed by literary writers and the story is used as an example of [[Introspection|introspective]] writing.<ref name="Freedman1980" /><ref name="Sellers2010" /><ref name="Fraser2011" />

==Publication==
''The Mark on the Wall'' has been included in a number of anthologies.

*Woolf, Virginia. "A Mark on the Wall." ''The Norton Anthology of English Literature.''Vol. F. Ed. 8th ed. Ed.Stephen Jahan Ramazani; Greenblatt; M. H. Abrahms; Jon Stallworthy. New York: W. W. Norton, 2005.
Woolf, Virginia. "A Mark on the Wall." ''Haunted House and other stories''. Hogarth Press, London, 1944.<ref name="Welsh2010"/>
*Woolf, Virginia. (28 March 2014). ''Monday or Tuesday: Eight Stories''. Start Classics. pp.&nbsp;39–. {{ISBN|978-1-60977-494-3}}.
*Woolf, Virginia. "The Mark on the Wall." ''The Wordsworth Collection of Classic Short Stories''. Wordsworth editions, 2007. pp.1334-.
